# VLAN Design

# Overview

The Corporate Office network is segmented using Virtual Local Area Networks (VLANs) to logically separate departments while sharing the same physical switching infrastructure.

VLAN segmentation reduces broadcast traffic, improves network organization, enhances security, and simplifies network administration.

Each department operates within its own Layer 2 broadcast domain while inter-VLAN communication is centrally managed by the Office router using Router-on-a-Stick.


# VLAN Architecture

The Office network currently consists of three VLANs.

```mermaid
graph TD
    Office-RTR[Office Router] --> |802.1Q Trunk| CAS[Core Access Switch]
    CAS        --> VL10[VLAN 10]
    CAS        --> VL20[VLAN 20]
    CAS        --> VL30[VLAN 30]
```

Each VLAN represents an independent Layer 2 network connected through managed switches.

---

# VLAN Assignment

| VLAN ID | Department | Purpose |
|----------|------------|---------|
| 10 | Admin |  Management and administrative devices  |
| 20 | Finance | Finance department devices |
| 30 | HR | Human Resources devices |

# VLAN Objectives

The VLAN implementation was designed to achieve the following objectives:

- Separate departmental traffic.
- Reduce unnecessary broadcast traffic.
- Improve network scalability.
- Simplify network management.
- Prepare the network for future access control policies using ACLs.

# Access Ports

End devices such as desktop computers, printers, and Access Points connect through access ports.

Each access port is assigned to exactly one VLAN.

Example:

| Device        | Switch Port   | VLAN      |
|---------------|---------------|-----------|
| Admin PC      | Fa0/2         | VLAN 10   |
| Finance PC    | Fa0/5         | VLAN 20   |
| HR PC         | Fa0/9         | VLAN 30   |

# Trunk Links

Communication between the Office switch and the Office router is provided through an IEEE 802.1Q trunk.

The trunk carries traffic from all configured VLANs over a single physical interface.

```mermaid
graph TD
    Office-RTR[Office Router] --> | 802.1Q Trunk | Office-SW[Office Switch]
```

This allows the router to create separate logical subinterfaces for each VLAN while using only one physical Ethernet connection.


# Wireless VLAN Integration

The Office network supports both wired and wireless connectivity.

Wireless Access Points are connected to the switching infrastructure and provide Wi-Fi access for laptops and smartphones.

Wireless devices are assigned to the appropriate VLAN according to the network design, allowing them to communicate with other devices within the same department while maintaining VLAN segmentation.


# Inter-VLAN Communication

Since each VLAN is an independent Layer 2 network, communication between VLANs is not possible through switching alone.

Inter-VLAN routing is performed by the Office router using Router-on-a-Stick.

Traffic flow between VLANs follows the path below.

```mermaid
graph TD
client[Client]

client --> Office-SW[Office Switch] --> |802.1Q Trunk| Office-RTR[Office Router]

Office-RTR --> Office-SW1[Back to Office Switch]

Office-SW1 --> vlan[Destination VLAN]
```

This allows devices in different VLANs to communicate while maintaining logical separation.


# VLAN Design Considerations

The VLAN implementation follows several enterprise networking best practices:

- One VLAN per department.
- Logical separation of users.
- Centralized routing.
- Simplified network administration.
- Support for future ACL implementation.
- Support for future expansion without redesigning the network.


# Current Limitations

The current VLAN implementation provides unrestricted inter-VLAN communication through the Office router.

Traffic filtering between VLANs has not yet been implemented.

Future versions of the project will introduce Access Control Lists (ACLs) to enforce communication policies between departments.


# Summary

The VLAN implementation provides logical segmentation of the Corporate Office while maintaining efficient communication through Router-on-a-Stick.

Current implementation includes:

- Three departmental VLANs
- IEEE 802.1Q trunking
- Router-on-a-Stick
- Wired and wireless connectivity
- Enterprise-ready modular design